        <para>This test is performed to measure the gas blow-by (past the piston into the crankcase) in terms of
            crankcase pressure. The test is accomplished by directing all crankcase venting through a single orifice of
            predetermined size (0.406 in. dia.). The higher the pressure at the orifice, the greater the rate of
            blow-by.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <important>
                <para>FREQUENT CHECKS OF CRANKCASE PRESSURE WILL HELP MONITOR POWER CYLINDER CONDITION. CRANKCASE
                    PRESSURES HIGHER THAN THE MAXIMUM SPECIFIED, COUPLED WITH HIGHER THAN NORMAL OIL CONSUMPTION RATE,
                    SIGNAL THE NEED TO INVESTIGATE POWER CYLINDER CONDITION.
                </para>
            </important>
        </specpara>
        <para>MEASURE CRANKCASE PRESSURE AS FOLLOWS:
            <emph type="bold">1988 MODEL YEARS AND BEFORE [S-SERIES APPLICATIONS]</emph>
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Plug the CDR valve with a cardboard gasket as follows: Refer to Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef4600532">5.32</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Loosen and remove the CDR valve fasteners (bolts, nuts and washers).</para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>DO NOT DISCONNECT HOSES FROM THE CDR, VALVE COVER OR INTAKE MANIFOLD.</para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Lift the CDR valve assembly with seal ring and insert a clean piece of cardboard over
                    the opening in the CDR valve mounting bracket.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Reinstall the CDR valve over the cardboard and fasten securely.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>BE SURE THE CARDBOARD SEALS THE CDR VALVE OPENING COMPLETELY. THE RUBBER SEAL RING MUST BE
                            ON THE CDR VALVE ASSEMBLY NOT ON THE BRACKET, TO PREVENT THE CARDBOARD GASKET FROM BEING
                            CUT. A CUT GASKET WILL GIVE FALSE CRANCKCASE PRESSURE READINGS.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">* - Manual specified with latest revision</emph>
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mount the orifice restrictor tool (ZTSE-4146) on the oil fill tube.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Connect a water manometer or magnahelic gauge (Tool No. ZTSE-2239) as shown in Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef4600532">5.32</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check crankcase pressure at rated speed, no load (engine at normal operating temperature).
                Pressure must not be greater than 6 in. H2O. Pressure greater than that specified indicates higher than
                normal blow-by. Record the reading on CGED-440-*, in the 1st check box.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">After test results are obtained, remove cardboard gasket, discard and reinstall CDR valve.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>PRESSURE READINGS OBTAINED WITH THIS RESTRICTOR MUST NOT BE USED AS THE MAIN SOURCE OF ENGINE
                        CONDITION. OIL CONSUMPTION TREND DATA MUST ALSO BE USED IF THE PRESSURE READINGS ARE BEYOND THE
                        SPECIFIED LIMITS. NEITHER CHANGES IN OIL CONSUMPTION TRENDS NOR CRANKCASE PRESSURE TRENDS CAN
                        ESTABLISH A SPECIFIC COMPONENT PROBLEM, BUT ARE INDICATORS THAT POWER CYLINDER PROBLEMS EXIST.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="ef4600532" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11741" filename="../figcg1/CG11741.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.32 Crankcase Pressure Test [1988 MODEL YEAR AND PRIOR]</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">* - Manual specified with latest revision</emph>
            </para>
            <para>MEASURE CRANKCASE PRESSURE AS FOLLOWS:
                <emph type="bold">1989 MODEL YEARS AND BEYOND [3000 AND 4000 SERIES APPLICATIONS]</emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Plug the CDR valve with a cardboard gasket as follows: Refer to Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef4600533">5.33</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Loosen and remove the CDR valve fasteners (bolts, nuts and washers) at the mounting
                    bracket on the left valve cover.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>DO NOT DISCONNECT HOSES FROM THE CDR TO THE INTAKE MANIFOLD.</para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Lift the CDR valve assembly
                    <emph type="bold">with seal ring</emph>and insert a clean piece of cardboard over the opening in the
                    CDR valve mounting bracket.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Reinstall the CDR valve over the cardboard and fasten securely.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>BE SURE THE CARDBOARD SEALS THE CDR VALVE OPENING COMPLETELY. THE RUBBER SEAL RING MUST BE
                            ON THE CDR VALVE ASSEMBLY NOT ON THE BRACKET, TO PREVENT THE CARDBOARD GASKET FROM BEING
                            CUT. A CUT GASKET WILL GIVE FALSE CRANKCASE PRESSURE READINGS.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mount the orifice restrictor tool (ZTSE-4146) with crankcase resrictor (ZTSE-4284) on the
                oil fill tube located on the right valve cover.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Connect a water manometer or magnahelic gauge (Tool No. ZTSE-2239) as shown in Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef4600533">5.33</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check crankcase pressure at rated speed, no load (engine at normal operating temperature).
                Pressure must not be greater than 6 in. H2O. Pressure greater than that specified indicates higher than
                normal blow-by. Record the reading on CGED-440-*, in the 1st check box.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">After test results are obtained, remove cardboard gasket, discard and reinstall CDR valve.
            </para>
            <figure id="ef4600533" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg14496" filename="../figcg1/CG14496.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.33 Crankcase Pressure Test [1989 MODEL YEAR AND BEYOND]</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">* - Manual specified with latest revision</emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
